## Best Practices & Recommendations

### Version Management
- ✅ **Keep dependencies updated**: Regular updates for security and performance
- ✅ **Pin major versions**: Use `~>` for minor updates, exact versions for critical deps
- ✅ **Test thoroughly**: Especially with newer versions like Ruby 3.4.4 and Node 23.x

### Performance Optimization
- ✅ **Use Vite**: Faster than Webpacker for asset compilation
- ✅ **Leverage Redis**: For caching and session storage
- ✅ **Background jobs**: Use Sidekiq for heavy processing
- ✅ **Database indexing**: Proper indexing for PostgreSQL queries

### Security Best Practices
- ✅ **Keep Devise updated**: Latest versions include security fixes
- ✅ **Use Sentry**: For production error monitoring
- ✅ **Rate limiting**: Rack Attack for API protection
- ✅ **Input sanitization**: DOMPurify for frontend, Rails built-ins for backend

### Development Workflow
- ✅ **Use pnpm**: More efficient than npm/yarn
- ✅ **Vitest over Jest**: Better Vite integration
- ✅ **Histoire over Storybook**: Lighter alternative for component docs
- ✅ **Composition API**: Modern Vue.js development pattern

### Migration Considerations
- ⚠️ **Vuex to Pinia**: Consider migrating for better TypeScript support
- ⚠️ **Node 23.x**: Ensure all dependencies are compatible
- ⚠️ **Ruby 3.4.4**: Test thoroughly with all gems

## Architecture Patterns

### Backend Patterns
- **MVC**: Standard Rails Model-View-Controller
- **Service Objects**: Business logic in `app/services/`
- **Background Jobs**: Async processing with Sidekiq
- **Event-Driven**: Wisper for pub/sub patterns

### Frontend Patterns
- **Component-Based**: Vue.js single-file components
- **Composition API**: Modern Vue.js development
- **Module Federation**: Separate apps (dashboard, widget, portal)
- **State Management**: Vuex for global state

This stack provides a modern, scalable foundation for a real-time customer support platform with excellent developer experience and production reliability.
